Machine Learning : Image recognition using neural network (MLP & CNN)

Rishee Barthakur¶

In this project we are doing image classification using tensorflow(keras). We have a dataset where we have diffferent images of airplane, automobile, bird,cat, deer, dog , frog, horse, ship and truck. The pictures are in RGB color, each color has a dimension of 32 X 32 X 3 stored in X and the Y value here contain the lables in the from of numbers corrosponding to the class_name array. Our main task is to porform MLP (Multilayer Perceptron) and CNN (Convolutional neural network) and compare their performance.
Our majot tasks:

PART 1¶
  1. Load the data
  2. Split the data train and test set.
  3. From train set split the data into train and validation set.
  4. Show images form train, validation and test set.
  5. Make MLP model
  6. Hyperparameter tuning of the model and save the model using directory
  7. Test the model in test set by calling the model if it exists on the dir after training it for 1 epoch.
  8. Create confusion matrix and f1 score of the model
PART 2¶
  1. Make a CNN model for the same train, test and validation set
  2. Perform hyperparameter tuning of the model and save the model using directory
  3. Test the model using test set by calling the model if it exists on the dir after training it for 1 epoch.
  4. Create confusion matrix and f1 score of the model
  5. Compare the result of both the model MLP and CNN

Showing Images¶

Creating a function to show the images from the train, validation and the test set.
x and y are the parameters for the independent and dependent variables. We are showing total 20 images which containes 4 rows(num_row) and 5 columns (num_col) which will be passed in the subplots() to generate 20 images.

How to show random images?
We are showing random images everytime we run the loop. In order to select random images we have used random.randint(31) which will generate random numbers everytime between 0-31. Because the len() of height and width is 32 so range(0,31) will consider 32 values in python. Then the randim number has been passed as in index in X[index] and y[index] which shows us the image with correct lables.

In [10]:
def showImg(x,y):
    #x is for independent variables X_train
    #y is for dependent variables Y_train    
    num_row = 4
    num_col = 5
    # plot images
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(num_row, num_col, figsize=(10,5))
    for i in range(20):
        ax = axes[i//num_col, i%num_col]
        #FOR RANDOM VALUES
        index = random.randint(31)
        ax.imshow((x[index]),cmap="binary", interpolation = "hamming")
        ax.set_axis_off()
        ax.set_title((class_names[y[index]]))
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

MLP¶

Creating MLP model with Sequential(), this function will make the model run in a sequence manner conrrospondin to all the layers from to to bottom. The Flatten layer will create 1D array from the input_shape=[32,32,3].
Dropout: It can be added in each layer of the network which helps in preventing overfitting of the model by stopping the complex co-adaptations on the training data.
Dense: This is the hidden layer. We have total 3 Dense layers in this network with 300, 100 and 10 neurons in each layers respectively. This layer hyperparameters such as activation function, kernel_initializer and many more but we are only considering 2 hyperparameters with the number of neurons.
activation: activation function in hidden layer is used to define the transformation of weighted sum from input layer to output layer. We have used relu as an activation function so basically relu(rectified linear activation function) is used to transform the all negative inputs to 0 in the output layer and for positive input it will remain positive. It is a linear function and it performs well compared to other activation functions. softmax has been used in the last layer because softmax is responsible for the classification
kernel_initializer: This is a regularization method whihc is used to avoid the overfitting of the model by initializing the weights and lecun_normal draws samples from a truncated normal distribution.
model.summary(): It is used for showing the architecture of the model.
model.compile(): sparse_categorical_crossentropy will show the loss on both the train and the validation and matrics=["accuracy"] will show the accuracy of both sets and we have used SDG as an optimer which is randomly select datapoints while running the algorithm .

PART 2
In the part 2 of the project we will perform CNN (convolutional neural network ) which is slightly differnt than the MLP and it is considered as better performer for image recognition compared to MLP. CNN contains convolutional layer, pooling layer and fully connected layer. We can increase or decrease the number of layers.
Conv2d : This is the convolution layer it takes the pixels from an input image and helps in recognizing the patterns, we have passed filters=64 which represents 64 nodes, kernal_size=7 represents the widthxheight of the filter, activation="relu" is used to make the negative output as 0., padding="SAME" is used to provide enough pixels in the covolutional layer to train our model and the input_shape consists of our input dimension. softmax has been used in the last layer for the classification.
MaxPolling2D : This is the pooling layer it shrinks the image by only considering the maximum values from the pixel array and convert it into 2D array.MaxPooling2D(2) indicates pooling size referes to 2 X 2 kernel.
Flatten(): Then we flatten the model as the way we have done in MLP which will a 1D array.
Dense(): We have used 2 Dense layers which are fully connected layers as MLP with relu as an activation function and the last layer consists of softman for the classification of the images.
BatchNormalization() : It is used for standardizing the inputs to a layer for each mini-batch to another layer.
Optimizer : We have used SGD optimizer to train our model.

Hyperparameter Tuning - CNN¶

This time we reduced the number of filters and the filter size in each layer. And we have also removed one Dense layer, and the remaing layers are having less neurons compared to the previous model. Also we have used Dropout rate 0.1 (valus less than 0.5 is giving better result) which prevents the model to overfit. Moreover we have used kernel_initalizer="he_normal" which is a regularization method used to avoid overfitting with ReLU as it finds the good variance from distribution.
Here, instead of SGD we have used adam which is a quite popular optimizer for image recognition, it combines the momentum of AdaGrad and RMSProp.

def callingModel():
  if os.path.isdir("barthakur_rishee-CNN"):
    CNN_model = keras.models.load_model("barthakur_rishee-CNN")
    print("Architeture CNN")
    CNN_model.summary()
    CNN_model.fit(X_train,y_train, epochs=1, validation_data=(X_valid,y_valid))
    return CNN_model
    
  else:
    print("Architecture CNN")
    CNN_model.summary()
    CNN_model.fit(X_train,y_train, epochs=100, validation_data=(X_valid,y_valid))
    CNN_model.evaluate(X_test, y_test)
    return CNN_model
CNN_model = callingModel()

Comparision¶

MLP
Our MLP model did not provide a good accuracy. the accuracy of the model is varing from 50% - 52% (Because of SGD) on the test and validation set and for thetest set it around(52% - 52%) which proves that the model is going overfitting the data.
CNN
CNN seems to be better than the MLP as it gave an accuracy approximately 76% on the Train set , 75% on the test set and 75% on the validation set.
The F1 score of CNN is 0.76 and for MLP it was 0.52 so the CNN is considered to be a better ANN for this project.
